oindent Then it is possible to compute integrals of the form  egin{equation*} \int_{\mathfrak{a}_j} (y-x_{j})^mf(y)^k dy \end{equation*} 
oindent where ${\mathrm{diam}\,} \mathfrak{a}_j <  rac{1}{2\eta}$ to within precision $\delta$ in space logarithmic in $m$, $k$, $\log \eta$ and $\log 1/\delta$. \end{theorem}  egin{remark} We note that if $f$ is analytic in $[a,b]$, then such a constant $\eta$ always exists. In fact, if we let $ho$ to be a strict lower bound of the set of all the radii of convergence of the Taylor series with centers in $[a,b]$ (note that $ho>0$ by compactness), then the integral Cauchy formula implies that, for any $x\in[a,b]$  egin{equation*} |\partial^{k}f(x)| \leq  rac{Mk!}{ho^{k}} \end{equation*} where $M$ is any upper bound of $f$ over $[a,b]^{ho}=\{z\in\mathbb{C}: |z-x|\leqho 	ext{ for some }x\in [a,b]\}$. \end{remark} To prove the above theorem, we first show that if $f$ satisfies the above constraints, then it is possible to compute its Taylor coefficients in logarithmic space.  egin{lemma} \label{taylor} Assume $f$ is log-space computable, smooth, and satisfies $|\partial^{k}f(x)| \leq k!\eta^{k}$ for all $x$ in the domain. Then for any $x_c$, we can write  egin{equation*} f(x) = \sum_{k} a_{k}(x-x_c)^k \end{equation*} 
oindent The value of $a_{k}$ is then computable to within precision $\delta$ in space logarithmic in $k$, $\log 1/\eta$, and $\log 1/\delta$. \end{lemma}  egin{proof} We claim that if we choose $	au = \delta \eta^{-(k+1)}k^{-(k+2)}2^{-k}$, then  egin{equation}\label{coeffbound} \left| \dfrac{\sum_{i=0}^{k}f(x+i	au)(-1)^{k-i} inom{k}{i}}{k!	au^k} - a_kight| \leq \delta \end{equation} Note that since $f$ is computable in log-space, the quantity on the LHS of equation ef{coeffbound} is computable in space $O(\log k + \log\log 1/	au) = O(\log k + \log\log \eta + \log\log 1/\delta)$, as desired. To prove equation ef{coeffbound}, recall that the Lagrange remainder theorem for Taylor series says that for any $x$ (within the radius of convergence of the Taylor series about $x_c$), we can write  egin{equation*} f(x) = \left(\sum_{i=0}^{k} a_{i}(x-x_c)^iight) + \dfrac{f^{(k+1)}(\xi)}{(k+1)!}(x-x_c)^{k+1} \end{equation*} 
oindent for some $\xi$ between $x_c$ and $x$. Write $f(x) = \left(\sum_{i=0}^{k} a_{i}(x-x_c)^iight) + R_{k+1}(x)$. By our constraint on $f$, we know that $\left| rac{f^{(k+1)}(\xi)}{(k+1)!}ight| \leq \eta^{k+1}$, so we can rewrite this as  egin{equation*} \left| R_{k+1}(x) ight| \leq \eta^{k+1}(x-x_c)^{k+1} \end{equation*} Next, recall the following binomial identities. For all $r < k$, we have that  egin{equation*} \sum_{i=0}^{k}i^{r}(-1)^{k-i} inom{k}{i} = 0 \end{equation*} 
oindent On the other hand, when $r=k$, we have that  egin{equation*} \sum_{i=0}^{k}i^{k}(-1)^{k-i} inom{k}{i} = k! \end{equation*} Substituting in the Taylor expansion for $f$ and applying the above binomial identities, we see that  egin{eqnarray*} \left|\dfrac{\sum_{i=0}^{k}f(x+i	au)(-1)^{k-i} inom{k}{i}}{k!	au^k} - a_kight| &=& \left|\dfrac{\sum_{i=0}^{k}R_{k+1}(x+i	au)(-1)^{k-i} inom{k}{i}}{k!	au^k} ight| \ &\leq & \dfrac{1}{k!	au^k}\sum_{i=0}^{k}\left|\eta^{k+1}i^{k+1}	au^{k+1} inom{k}{i}ight| \ &\leq & \dfrac{	au \eta^{k+1}}{k!}\sum_{i=0}^{k}k^{k+1}2^{k} \ &\leq & \dfrac{	au \eta^{k+1}k^{k+2}2^{k}}{k!} \ &\leq & \delta \end{eqnarray*} 
oindent as desired. \end{proof} We can now prove Theorem ef{analytic}.  egin{proof}[Proof of Theorem~ef{analytic}] We wish to compute the integral  egin{equation*} \int_{\mathfrak{a}_j}(y-x_j)^{m}f(y)^k dy \end{equation*} 
oindent where we know that ${\mathrm{diam}\,} \mathfrak{a}_j <  rac{1}{2\eta}$. Write $f(y) = \sum a_i(y-x_j)^i$; by our assumption $|a_i| \leq \eta^{i}$ for all $i$.
